# Design Token Rules

## Token Architecture

Tokens follow a three-tier hierarchy:

```
PRIMITIVE (raw values)  →  SEMANTIC (intent)         →  COMPONENT (usage)
blue-500                →  color-action-primary       →  button-bg-default
```

## File Organization

- `packages/tokens/src/primitives/` — Raw values (colors, spacing scales, font stacks)
- `packages/tokens/src/semantic/` — Theme-mapped tokens (light.json, dark.json, high-contrast.json)
- Output: `packages/tokens/platforms/` — Built artifacts per platform

## Naming Convention

All tokens use kebab-case with this pattern:
`{category}-{property}-{element}-{variant}-{state}`

Examples:
- `color-action-primary` (semantic)
- `color-action-primary-hover` (semantic + state)
- `color-surface-default` (semantic)
- `spacing-md` (semantic)
- `font-size-heading-lg` (semantic)

## Adding a New Token

1. Add to the appropriate primitives file if the raw value doesn't exist
2. Map it in `semantic/light.json` (and `dark.json`, `high-contrast.json`)
3. Run `pnpm --filter @vcds/tokens build`
4. Verify output in `packages/tokens/platforms/`
5. If it affects components, update the CSS in `packages/css/`

## Style Dictionary Config

The build config is in `packages/tokens/style-dictionary.config.js`. It outputs:
- CSS custom properties (web)
- SCSS variables (web)
- JS/TS module exports (web)
- Swift enums (iOS)
- Kotlin objects (Android)
- XML resources (Android)

## Rules

- NEVER modify files in `packages/tokens/platforms/` — they are generated
- ALWAYS ensure color tokens meet WCAG 2.2 AA contrast ratios
- ALWAYS provide values for all three themes (light, dark, high-contrast)
- Use `rem` for spacing and typography, not `px`
